## Description

heronhaye

opened on Dec 19, 2018

Issue body actions

Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.
I want to, as root, run `systemctl --user` commands as another user, and get stdout and the exit code. I can `systemd-run --wait --uid myuser echo foobar`, and parse the output to get the unit filename and look at `journalctl`, but I can't get this to work for the command `systemctl --user status myservice.service`; `journalctl` shows

    `Dec 19 12:09:30 myhostname systemd[1]: run-u357387.service: Main process exited, code=exited, status=1/FAILURE
    Dec 19 12:09:30 myhostname systemd[1]: run-u357387.service: Failed with result 'exit-code'.
    `

Passing `--user` to `systemd-run` doesn't seem to help either, I immediately get `Failed to create bus connection: No such file or directory`.

Describe the solution you'd like
Instructions on how `systemd-run` can be used to run `systemctl --user` commands while root, for another user.

Describe alternatives you've considered
I can use `machinectl shell myuser@ /usr/bin/echo foobar`, and this method works for `systemctl --user` commands, but this loses the exit code.

Setting the `XDG_RUNTIME_DIR` and the `DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS` explicitly with `-E` in the `systemd-run` command works, but I have to get that info via `machinectl`. It seems a bit unwieldy to run both `machinectl` and `systemd-run`, and I'm also not sure if this is best practice or there is other config I should set up other than those environment variables.


